{"/service/ndnp/oru/batch_oru_keel_ver01/data/sn90066132/00295867425/1920070101/0094.xml":{"full_text":"VUE CAPITAL JOURNAL,\n1Z3 TT.'U\nLatest News\nWlllte Ualley to CMJojUMSPecig! Cor TMpg\nClaxtaTf\nBringing Up. Father By George McM anus\nHervioo, Inc.\ni Maruueritis an..1\nore visiting Lake\nof\nClaxtar July\nAgUBta,. Matthes\nLabish relatives.\nvrr anil Mrs. C. F. Rhoades, late\nf Trinidad. Colo., have bought\nJPrnitt Bros, r5 acres here, at 30U\nJper acre.\nAmong the recent graduates of\nSalem senior high school, well known\nfcere, were Mae Hall, Mattie Edith\nHarm an, Olive Klser and Norma\nglarys Webb.\nMr. and Mrs. Elmer Westley\nAstoria are the parents of a son.\nMr. and Mrs. Isaac Newton are\nIn receipt of letters from their so.i,\n.Walter Newton, well known hotal\nman who Is now located at Santa\nCatallna Island, and who is enthusi\nastic over the business outlook there.\nMr. and Mrs. Howard Bowen were\niflinner guests at the home of Mr. anJ\nMrs. Buthvyn Tourney of Chemawa\nSunday.\nMrs. Gus Noren and Mrs. John\nUphart visited .the John Westleys\nthis week. f\nI J I I vmi MSP AT I 1\n-ir-r TT1 L I f OLUY-TTIATiA -H THE CROWD-, I\nHEUO-JI-COMe UCHT-JUO-SE ORDER WRIT UriTU. \"r,, HARP w ir 1 1 THO ARC THE\ni \"P 1'- fJl\nims. I Ls9 ,.JJ I\nI f 1 1 n III II r-\nToday's Dallas News\nDallas, July 1. The industries of\nDallas are proving to t so numer\nous and valuable that Capital is seek\ning an anchorage here. Many new\nenterprises have begun recently\namong them, one of the best equip\nped locomotive and iron works that\ncan be found in the Willamette val\nley. A new process fruit drier, a can\naery and now another saw mill is\nbeing planned. Ed Hamilton, a veter\nan of the war with the rank of cap\ntain in the spruce division and for\nmerly associated with the Monmouth\nLumber Co., is moving his mill from\nthe Smith farm near Bridgeport\nwhere he has been operating the past\nyear. The mill will be located on the\nBpaulding site on North Levens\nstreet. They will begin operating with\na, 25,000 capacity and increase the\noutput In due course of time. He has\ncontracted for 3,000,000 feet of thn\nber near Salt Creek; The mill is to\nfee located near the LaCreole creek\nand a dam will be made to hold tho\nlogs.\nAuto Goes Over tirade\nAn auto accident unprecedented In\nthe history of the gas wagon occur\nred in the Butler district recently.\nMr. and Mrs. James Edwards and\nfamily were motoring home from\nWiilamina and on approaching .ho\nButler bridge, which is at right an-,\nBles with the county road, endeav\nored to make 'the turn while travel\ning too fast. Mrs. Kdwards was driv-\nIng and did not make the turn which\nresulted In a pitch over the side of\nthe bridge approach down an em\nbankment 30 feet f turning over sev\neral times, The ear jwiu completely\nwrecked but the oecflpartts were not\nInjured except for a few minor bruls\nea. Mr. Edwards is Interested in the\nSutler sawmill three miles from tho\naeene of the accident.\nDallas Veteran Married\nA beautiful wedding took place in\nHlllsboro at the home of Mr. and\nMrs. A. Branshaw on Wednesday,\nwhen their youngest daughter, Katie,\nwas united In marriage to Virgil R.\nJBallantyne of Dallas, a veteran of\nthe late war. Rev. V. A. Ballantyne\nof LewiHVille, a brother of the groom,\nofficiated\nThe bridal couple stood beneath a\nwhite bell which was overhung with\na bower of evergreen, Interspersed\nwith marguerites. The color scheme\nof the decorations being yellow and\nwhite.\nMiss Gussle Sigler was bridesmaid\nand Clyde Gibbs was best man. Two\n.little fairy like flower girls preceded\nthe bridal party followed by Master\nCecil Lightfoot carrying the wedding\n.ring In a white lily.\nAfter refreshments to about 70\nCuesls the couple was recipients of\nmany beautiful and useful gifts,\njtmong them being a Navajo blanKet\nfrom tho Camp Fire girls, of which\nthe bride was a popular member.\nJUr. and Mrs. Ballantyne will live on\nfinch street In their new home In\nJDallas.\nltlilli Nil mi Married\nAn early morning wedding was sol\nemnized at eight o'clock yesterday sit\nthe St. Phillips Cathouc church by\ni Kev. Father Phillips of Portland,\nwhen Miss Ruth Nuim became the\nbride of William F. Koenlgs ot Port\nland. The church was decorated with\nbeautiful blossoms and while flow\ners adorned the altar. The guests\nwere received at the entry by four\nmaidens who were daintily gowned\nIn white.\nThe Misses Lenore Preston, Grace\nForctto, Mildred Shaw and May Mc\nDonald were the receiving maidens\nwho carried shower bouquets and\nwore picture hats.\nMiss Alice Grant sang \"At Dawn\nIng\" and MIhs Dorothy Bennett play\neil (he wedding march.\nThe bride was attended by four\nbridesmaids and was met at the al\ntar by the groom and the Rev. Fath\ner Phillips. A simple and short wed\nding service was used.\nJrollowliiK the ceremony they left\nfor Victoria, B. C, on a short honey\nmoon and will soon return to Port\nland where they will live. Mrs. Koe\nBigs is a daughter of Mr. and Mrs.\ni. B. Nunn of this city and for the\nVast four years has been an instruct\nor In the Portland schools. Mr. Koe\natga la a real estate man In business\nla Portland.\na car load of Fords this week which\nis exceptional.\nEd Dunn, the confectionery man\nhas purchased the large home of Mr.\nCole on Birch etreet.\nFloyd Ellis met with an accident\nnear Amity while driving his new\ncoupe home from Portland which re\nsulted in a badly smashed up car;\nbut the occupants were not seriously\ninjured. The report Is he ran into a\nrut while going at a good speed, turn\ning the car over.\nMrs. Ethel Woods returned this\nweek from Seattle where she has\nbeen spending the past few weeks at\nthe home of Mr. and Mrs. A. G.\nRhodes. Mrs. Rhodes is Mrs. Woods'\nsister and is leaving within a few\ndays, accompanied by her husband,\nfor France where they will visit the\ndevastated regions which were the\nscene of the world war.\nOtto Carl John, son of Otto John,\nSr., of Grand Ronde, was In Dallas\nyesterday taking out his declaration\nof intention.\nMonmouth Man\nWeds Portland\nSchool Teacher\nMonmouth, Or., July 1. Edwin Nis,\nsen, local stock buyer, evidently e\nlieves in preparedness. Recently he\nrented the Goodman house on West\nstreet and furnished it for housekeep\ning. Then with the house In readiness\nhe went to Portland and married. As\nho has picked a normal town to live\nin, It was eminently proper that he\nshould marry a schoolma'am and this\nhe proceeded to do. The bride is Miss\nMargaret Cunningham, for five years a\nteacher in the Mt. Taber school in\nPortland. The ceremony took place\nSaturday and was performed at a.\nIt Is reported that E. B. Hamilton,\nwho planned to bring his sawmill to\nMonmouth, has concluded since to lo\ncate in Dallas.\nG. T. Boothby reports the sale this\nweek of 38 acres off of the William\nRlddell, Jr., farm to Edwin Nissan.\nThis is the southeast corner 01 the\nfarm coming up to the highway near\nthe Van Meter house. It includes 17\nacres of prunes and tho rest is sown\nto clover and rape.\nThiB week Ira Williams becomes the\nowner of the smaller of Mrs. Boots'\nhouses, located on the corner of Clay\nand Monmouth avenue. Consideration\n$600. G. T. Boothby handed the deal.\nMr. and Mrs. Boothby visited Sun\ndav with relatives in Corvallis,\nRepresentatives of the Monmouth\nChautauqua are canvassing this week\nfor the sale of tickets and nave met\nwith very encouraging results. They\nare Dresentinjr a well balanced pro\ngram and the fact is appreciated. Lo\ncally tickets are on sale at the follow\ning places: Winegars, Miler Mercan\ntile. Hill Son, Mulkey Son, Jonii\nson's, Morlan's. Children's tickets sell\nfor $1.10; students' $1.60, adults' $2.5\nJames Graham, who has been sick\nfor some time, is improving so as to\nbo able to be out of doors.\nh..mh.r r'hirin\nT.lnrtholm. who will move to me\nas soon as the house Is vacated,\nCannery Works\nDay And Night\nAt Silverton\nSllverton, Or., July 1. Operating\nwith a night and day crew the Silver\nton Cannery Packing plant is mak\nlnr the first season's run a marke\nsuccess. The company has handled\npratcically all the strawberries grown\nhere this season and this week started\nIn with the cherries which are being\nreecived in great quantity. Eight\ncents is the price paid for cherries.\nJ. L. Eidson sold $30 worth of cherries\nyesterday taken from two trees In his\nfront yard. The two trees, It is said,\nwill yield that much more before 'the\nPresbyterian parsonage in Portland by season Is over. The Silverton Can\nRev. Dorse.\nE. L. Farens, who recently sold his\nranch at Roseburg, was a visitor this\nweek with his relatives, Mr. and Mrs.\nJ. F. Moreland. Mr. Farrens Is travel\ning with his family by automobile to\nThe Dalles near where he expects to\nlocate.\nE. W. Staats was In Reedsport, Sat\nurday, attending tho sale of thorough\nbred Jerseys formerly belonging to\nhim. He sold the cows recently to a\nPortland promoter who shipped them\nto Myrtle Point and attempted a sale\nthere. Because advance notice had not\nbeen given to the Coos county agent\nand the latter had not time to verify\nthe pedigrees of the stock the Myrtle\nPoint sale proved a disappointment\nand the herd was moved to Reedsport.\nning company is undertaking to pro\nvide a market for all the fruit grown\nIn this vicinity.\nWilliam Noftsker, who has been\nvisiting his son, P. W. Noftsker, for\nfew weeks is viewing the sights at New\nport this week. He will spend som\ntime there before returning to his\nhome in the east.\nMrs. Earl Dedrick and Harley Smith\nof San Francisco, Cal,, are visiting at\nthe home of their parents, Mr. and\nMra. E. L. Smith.\nM. G. Cooley, former proprietor of\nthe Gem theater, who is traveling with\na stock company s leader of the or\nchestra, Is visiting his mother in the\ncity.\nLouis Wolfard sold his residence on\nWest Main street yesterday to August\nSafe THilk for infants invalids\nAon rUK\nHorlick's\nTie Original\nAvoid\nImitations\nand Substitute.\nPorlnfantMnvalldganilGrawlngChddren I Rich Mill, Matted Grain Extract In Powder\nThe Original Food-Drink For All Ages No Cooking Nourishing Digeatible\n3\nShattuck Motor company received\nWhen Folks\nQuit Coffee\nbecause of cost to\nhealth or purse, they\nnaturally drink\nInstant\nFostum\nThere's a Reason\nJk d Vacation j\n\"Quality\"\nFishing\nTackle\nNormal Summer\nSchool 'Attracts\nHost Of Students\nMonmouth, Or., July 1. The regis\ntration in summer school has reached\n465 which number added to the 60 en\nrolled at Pendleton makes a most\ngratifying total for the summer of\n1920.\nMr. Gentle will speak Friday morn\ning of this week at the normal exten\nsion is session at Pendleton.\nThe question of regular work on\nJuly 5th was referred by the president\nto the student body. The latter u\ncided to show their patriotism by os\nclarlng July 5th a holiday and they\nare planning some fitting celebration.\nTlie annual reception by the faculty\nto the students of the summer session\nwas held in the gymnasium last. Sat\nurday evening. Nearly every student\naccepted the invitation and the in\nformal \"get acquainted\" party proved\nvery enjoyable.\nThe first grouping of the students by\ncounties for the social activities oi\nthe session was made here, much spir\nit and enthusiasm being displayed by\neach group. Plans are now well un\nder way by the committees in tne\ngroups for picnics, social dancing and\nthe usual \"stunt\" program which is\ngiven in the chapel the last week in\nJuly.\nThe \"Norm\" the year book, publish\ned by the normal students, has been\nan entire financial success this year,\nunder the supervision of Miss Eugenia\nMcNaghten and her corps of workers.\nMiss Brenton gave the students and\nfaculty a very enjoyable chapel hour\nWednesday morning.\nThe chairman of the entertainment\ncommittee of the faculty has iui\nnounced the securing of some very at\ntractive numbers for the normal next\nyear. Among these are Frederick\nWard, well-known lecturer and inter\npreter of Shakespeare's plays, who will\nbe in Monmouth during the first term\nnf the next school year. Also two un\nfurnished by Jonn ivenun.; t.\nand Thomas Wilfred. Mr. Bangs wo\nis so well known as a humorous writer\nwill lecture and Mr. Wilfred will give\na most unique entertainment. He Is\nknown as a singer of old folksongs\nand ballads and player of the twelve\nstring arch-lute, and gives a program\nof English, Difnish and French trou\nbadour songs and music which has\nbeen much praised by audiences in\nVassar college and Mlnesota umvei-\nt the year will be alty. The above, an l\npleasure to me\nHighway Is CIommI.\nThe Columbia River highway be\ntween Cascade Locks and The Dalles\nIs closed to all traffic during working\nhours now while construction work is\nprogress uucoi-uiiik. 10 announcement\nby Stulu HUrhwuy Engineer Nunn Th.\n...111 Ko \"B\niu Hume Irom I'A\nto 1 o'clock noon und from 5 p m un\ntil 7 a. m.\nTho first airplane to cross the Ca\ncades from Eugene to Bend arrived\nat the latter place Monday.\npffl fey\nafe m\nLYKOUtold In-aHf1\"' \"clw\npiir. abort.\nFtfuM all suartltuUl.\nSummer\nLassitude\nSizzling days and swelt\nering nights wear down\nthe reserve force and\nleave the mind and body\nimpoverished. Rebuild\nyour energy and restore\nyour amoition wun\nThe Great General Tonic\nSold By All Reliablt Druttitlm\nSole Manufacturers:\nLYKO MEDICINE COMPANY\nNew York Kansas Ciry, Mo.\nFor sale by all Druggists. Always\nin stock at Perry's Drug Store.\nBABY\nCRIBS\nAll kinds at Reasonable\nm Prices\nCfioo Choo's\nLarge Stock of Various\nSizes, many prices\nVisit My Children's Department\nAnd see what we have for you\nMAX O.BUREN\n179 North Commercial Street, Salem.\n(non skid) O\nEXTRAVAGANCE has\ngone by the, board. Thrift\nis in the air. Men are buying\nwnere tne value is.\nh\nOuting Clothing for i\nMen and Women\nCamp Stoves\nFLASHLIGHTS CAMP AXES\nPOCKET KNIVES PACK SACKES\nSAFETY RAZO